International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Fri 21 Dec 2018 3:38 pm PST
Source: The Press-Enterprise, Orange County Register report [edited]
https://www.pe.com/2018/12/21/southern-californias-newcastle-disease-toll-on-chickens-rises-to-60000-including-commercial-flock/


After appearing to have taken the upper hand on the bird-killing Newcastle disease outbreak in Southern California, officials this month [December 2018] announced a commercial chicken flock in Riverside county had been infected and that mandatory euthanasia operations have expanded to include Riverside county's greater Perris area.

Since the outbreak of the virus in mid-May [2018], about 60 000 birds -- mostly chickens -- have been euthanized, according to Steve Lyle, spokesman for the California Department of Agriculture. Until this month [December 2018], the infected chickens were nearly all backyard show birds.

Virulent Newcastle disease is deadly and highly contagious among birds, but is not a food-safety problem, according to the US Department of Agriculture's [USDA] 15 Dec 2018 news release on the infection of the commercial flock. "No human cases of Newcastle disease have ever occurred from eating poultry products," according to the USDA. "Properly cooked poultry products are safe to eat. In very rare instances, people working directly with sick birds can become infected. Symptoms are usually very mild and limited to conjunctivitis and/or influenza-like symptoms."

Lyle said all the chickens at the operation were euthanized but referred additional questions regarding that flock to the USDA. USDA spokeswoman Lyndsay Cole said that in such cases, her agency does not identify the business affected or its exact location. It is the 1st recorded case of Newcastle disease in commercial poultry since 2003.

Viral flare-up
--------------
As of mid-November [2018], the outbreak had been eradicated from 9 areas in Los Angeles, San Bernardino, Riverside, and Ventura counties. That left 3 areas with mandatory euthanasia orders: Compton in Los Angeles county, Muscoy in San Bernardino county and in the Mira Loma area of Jurupa Valley in Riverside county. At that time, about 54 000 birds had been euthanized.

Those 3 areas continue under mandatory euthanasia orders, with Perris added to during the week of 7 Dec 2018. After the last birds are euthanized in an area, it must remain free of infected birds for at least 4 months before the orders are lifted.

Virulent Newcastle disease, formerly known as exotic Newcastle disease, affects nearly all species of birds, according to the USDA. There is no cure, vaccinated birds can be infected, and birds can die without displaying symptoms. Symptoms, when exhibited, can include sneezing, gasping for air, nasal discharge, coughing, greenish diarrhea, tremors, and swelling around the eyes and neck.

The USDA recommends bird owners avoid visits to other poultry farms or bird owners during an outbreak. Those who do make visits should change clothes and clean their hands and shoes before entering their own bird area. Birds returning from shows should be isolated from other birds for 30 days. New birds should also be separated from other birds for at least 30 days. Egg trays, crates, vehicles ,and tires should be disinfected.

Owners who believe their birds may be infected should call the CDFA [California Department of Food and Agriculture] sick bird hotline at 866-922-2473.

2003 outbreak
-------------
The current outbreak is relatively small compared with the last rash of cases in the state. In 2002 and 2003, nearly 4 million birds on 2500 premises were euthanized, according to Lyle. That included 22 commercial poultry operations.

"No one wants their birds euthanized," Lyle told the Southern California News Group last month [November 2018]. "In fact, we don't like the idea of euthanizing birds at all, but we know scientifically this is the only option to stop the spread of the virus and eradicate the disease. Most residents understand what we're all up against when we share specific information with them, particularly if they have seen what this virus does to poultry. It is a highly contagious killer of poultry."

[byline: Martin Wisckol]

